instance virtual_to_physical_interaction : DTDFVocab:VirtualToPhysical [
    base:desc "The DT influences the PT through the following interactions: (1) **Control Commands**: The DT sends commands (e.g., turn heatbed/fan on/off) via the **RabbitMQ server** to the low-level driver on the Raspberry Pi. (2) **Parameter Updates**: The DT can adjust the **bang-bang controller parameters** (LL, UL, H, C) dynamically based on model predictions or optimization. (3) **Reconfiguration**: The DT may trigger reconfiguration of the PT (e.g., changing fan voltage from 12V to 18V) to improve temperature uniformity, as demonstrated in experiments. The **RabbitMQ server** acts as a message broker to synchronize these commands."
]

instance twinning_time_scale : DTDFVocab:TimeScale [
    base:desc "The DT operates on **real-time and quasi-real-time time scales**: (1) **Real-Time Control Loop**: The bang-bang controller on the Raspberry Pi executes at a **sub-second frequency** (e.g., 100ms–1s intervals) to regulate temperature based on sensor feedback. (2) **Quasi-Real-Time Calibration**: Model calibration occurs offline or during low-load periods, using historical data trajectories (e.g., 200J heating events over ~2s) to optimize parameters via iterative least-squares methods. (3) **Event-Driven Updates**: DT-to-PT synchronization happens asynchronously via RabbitMQ, with latency dependent on network conditions (local deployment minimizes delays)."
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The DT constellation follows a **cyber-physical integration framework** with the following orchestration: (1) **Physical Layer**: PT hardware (sensors, actuators, Raspberry Pi). (2) **Communication Layer**: RabbitMQ server acts as a message broker, decoupling PT components (sensors, actuators) from the DT. (3) **Virtual Layer**: DT runs on the same Raspberry Pi (or remotely) and includes: (a) **Simulation Models** (A and B), (b) **Calibration Engine** (Scipy-based), (c) **Control Logic** (bang-bang with parameter tuning). (4) **Feedback Loop**: The DT continuously updates models via calibration and adjusts PT behavior through RabbitMQ commands. The architecture is **modular**, allowing future extensions (e.g., cloud-based DT)."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The DT covers the following lifecycle stages of the PT: (1) **As Designed**: Models (A and B) are derived from theoretical assumptions (e.g., uniform temperature, negligible heatbed inertia in Model A). (2) **As Manufactured**: Calibration adjusts models to match the **actual physical prototype** (e.g., styrofoam box, heatbed dimensions). (3) **As Operated**: The DT continuously monitors and optimizes the PT during runtime, adapting to environmental changes (e.g., room temperature fluctuations) and component wear (e.g., heatbed efficiency degradation). The DT does not explicitly cover **end-of-life** stages (e.g., decommissioning)."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Fidelity and validity are addressed through: (1) **Model Assumptions**: Validated experimentally (e.g., Assumption 1 on uniform temperature tested via sensor placement in Fig. 9/11). (2) **Calibration Accuracy**: Model parameters are optimized using **least-squares minimization** (Scipy) to reduce residual errors between predictions and real data. (3) **Uncertainty Quantification**: Model B (4 parameters) accounts for heatbed thermal inertia, improving fidelity over Model A (2 parameters). (4) **Verification**: Experimental results (e.g., Fig. 10/12) show temperature discrepancies (±7°C to ±6°C) due to fan voltage adjustments, validating model assumptions. (5) **Error Handling**: The low-level driver includes a **safe protocol** to prevent unsafe PT states (e.g., overheating)."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "The DT connects to the PT via: (1) **Network Protocol**: **RabbitMQ** (AMQP-based) for asynchronous message passing between the Raspberry Pi and DT components. (2) **Physical Interface**: (a) **1-Wire Bus**: Connects DS18S20 sensors to Raspberry Pi GPIO. (b) **GPIO Pins**: Control heatbed/fan via MOSFETs (optocouplers isolate signals). (3) **Data Flow**: Temperature data is sampled at **sub-second intervals** and transmitted to RabbitMQ. Control commands are pushed from DT to PT with **low latency** (local deployment). (4) **Redundancy**: No explicit failover mechanisms, but RabbitMQ supports **message persistence** and **acknowledgments** for reliability."
